				Process scale is about getting out of your own way: reduce your resource conflicts. In programming, we talk about orders of magnitude of complexity relative to data count, e.g., O(n), but practically the bottleneck can be any of a number of resources.  Commonly these bottlenecks are some combination of latency and throughput across CPU, storage, and network.

The downside to this analysis is it usually does not take into account how the bottleneck could change over time as costs, throughputs, and latencies improve at the unit level.  Take a look at three graphs I shamelessly pilfered from the <a href="http://www.iaventures.com/">IA Ventures</a> <a href="http://www.slideshare.net/BenSiscovick/the-business-of-big-data-ia-ventures-8577588">presentation on Big Data</a> at  <a href="http://generalassemb.ly/">General Assembly</a> almost exactly one year ago.

<a href="http://www.howweknowus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/cpucurve.png"><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-932" title="cpucurve" src="http://www.howweknowus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/cpucurve-e1341949921673-150x121.png" alt="" width="150" height="121" /></a>

<a href="http://www.howweknowus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/storagecurve.png"><img class="alignleft size-thumbnail wp-image-933" title="storagecurve" src="http://www.howweknowus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/storagecurve-e1341950011838-150x129.png" alt="" width="150" height="129" /></a>

