All of the manufactured components are decreasing exponentially in cost over time.  Now, compare the oft-neglected non-fungible elements of our information economy, people.

[caption id="attachment_934" align="alignnone" width="300"]<a href="http://www.howweknowus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/peoplecurve.png"><img class="size-medium wp-image-934 " title="peoplecurve" src="http://www.howweknowus.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/peoplecurve-300x225.png" alt="" width="300" height="225" /></a> Source: Bureau of Labor Statistics: Professional, scientific, and technical services ftp://ftp.bls.gov/pub/suppl/eci.echistrynaics.txt[/caption]

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Through the magic of mass manufacturing, we have taken hardware out of the running as a cost bottleneck.  We need to turn the goal of getting more out of our computers to <strong><em>using computers to get more out of our people</em></strong>.

